{{notability|Products|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox video game | title = Emergency 4: Global Fighters for Life | collapsible = no | image = File:Emergency 4 - Global Fighters for Life Coverart.png | caption = Emergency 4 box art | developer = [[Sixteen Tons Entertainment]] | publisher = {{vgrelease|EU|[[Take-Two Interactive]]|UK|[[Bluestone Interactive]]}} | designer = | series = ''[[Emergency (series)|Emergency]]'' | engine = | released = {{vgrelease|EU|April 13, 2006}} | genre = [[Real-time strategy]] | modes = [[Single player]], [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]] | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] }} {{Infobox video game |title = 911: First Responders |collapsible = yes |state = collapsed |image = File:911 First Responders cover art.jpg |caption = 911: First Responders box art |developer = [[Empire Interactive]] |publisher = {{vgrelease|NA|[[Atari, Inc. (Atari, SA subsidiary)|Atari, Inc.]]}} |series = |released = {{vgrelease|NA|June 22, 2007<ref name="ign">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/911-first-responders/pc-899435 | title=911: First Responders | publisher=IGN | accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref>}} |platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] }} '''''Emergency 4: Global Fighters for Life''''' (known as '''''911: First Responders''''' in North America) is a [[simulation video game]] developed by German studio Sixteen Tons Entertainment allowing users to manage [[emergency service]]s on a variety of [[accident]] and/or accident scenes.
==Gameplay== The player becomes head of operations in a fictional rescue management organization in command of a number of vehicles and staff from the fire department, medical rescue, police, and technical services. The player has to react to a variety of events against a background of continuous day/night rotation and constantly changing weather conditions.<ref name="giantbomb">{{cite web |url=http://www.giantbomb.com/emergency-4-global-fighters-for-life/3030-15091/ | title=Emergency 4: Global Fighter for Life | publisher=Giant Bomb | accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name="nowgamer">{{cite web |url=http://www.nowgamer.com/pc/pc-reviews/906639/emergency_4_global_fighters_for_life.html | title=Emergency 4: Global Fighters For Life | publisher=NowGamer | accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref>
The game includes 20 missions, the ability to manage a team of emergency response professionals, ability to manage a variety of emergency response vehicles, with mandatory free play intermissions at every interim, and the Endless and Challenge free play modes.<ref name="giantbomb" /><ref name="nowgamer" /><ref name="ataricom">{{cite web |url=http://www.atari.com/buy-games/simulation/911-first-responders | title=911: First Responders | publisher=Atari | accessdate=August 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name="wsgf">{{cite web |url=http://www.wsgf.org/dr/911-first-responders | title=911: First Responders | work=Widescreen Gaming Forum | accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref>
''Emergency 4'' boasts several improvements in user-friendliness over previous games in the ''[[Emergency (series)|Emergency]]'' series. For instance, it is possible to dispatch several vehicles at the same time, order them to arrive at a specific location, there's a simple counter for the number of casualties in the area of operations, and idle [[emergency physician]]s seek out nearby untended casualties.
A deluxe release includes three extra missions and support for voice commands.
