{{Infobox person | name = Ken Forsse | imagesize = | image = | caption = | birth_name = Earl Kenneth Forsse | birth_date = {{birth date|1936|09|17|}} | birth_place =[[Bellwood, Nebraska]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2014|03|19|1936|9|25|mf=yes}} | death_place =[[Laguna Woods, California]] | known_for = Creator of ''[[Teddy Ruxpin]]''<ref>{{cite news|title= Problems of Toy's Producer Leave Its Creator in a Bind|work= The Los Angeles Times|date=January 19, 1988|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-01-19/business/fi-36933_1_teddy-ruxpin |accessdate=2010-03-04 | first=James | last=Bates}}</ref> | death_cause = [[Congestive heart failure]] | occupation = author | spouse = Jan Forsse (m. unknown-his death 2014) | children = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Earl Kenneth "Ken" Forsse''' (September 17, 1936 – March 19, 2014) was an [[United States|American]] inventor, author, and producer who created the toy [[Teddy Ruxpin]] and the subsequent animated series ''[[The Adventures of Teddy Ruxpin]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title= Alchemy II Makes Technology Cuddly Company Tries to Conjure Up Cash With New Talking Bear |publisher= The Los Angeles Times|date=November 24, 1985|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1985-11-24/business/fi-1921_1|accessdate=2010-08-22 | first=Alan | last=Goldstein}}</ref><ref>Lovable Teddy Ruxpin evolves from toy to animated star of his own half-hour program thanks to Crawley Films, Toronto Star - October 31, 1987</ref>
After working for [[The Walt Disney Company]], [[Sid & Marty Krofft]] Entertainment and other entertainment companies, he founded Alchemy II, Inc. One of Alchemy II's first projects was building the animatronic characters used on the television show ''[[Welcome to Pooh Corner]]''. Forsse and his team then brought Teddy Ruxpin to the marketplace. Teddy Ruxpin became the top selling toy of 1985 and 1986<ref name="PRWeb">[http://www.emediawire.com/releases/2006/9/emw439779.htm Teddy Ruxpin Earns Top Spot in 2006 Toy Awards]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, PRWeb, September 21, 2006. Accessed February 27, 2008.</ref><ref name="Barmash">Barmash, Isadore. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE0DE153AF93AA25750C0A961948260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all "Talking Deals"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 19, 1987. Accessed February 27, 2008.</ref> and was made by [[Worlds of Wonder (toy company)|Worlds of Wonder]].
In 2005, Alchemy II made an agreement with toy manufacturer BackPack Toys to have Teddy Ruxpin back on the shelves yet again and the toy made a return in 2006 before being discontinued again in 2010. In addition, the animated TV series was released for the first time on DVD in 2008.<ref name="BW">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2005_May_24/ai_n13776117 "He's Back! BackPack Toys Awakens Teddy Ruxpin from Hibernation"]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Business Wire, May 24, 2005. Accessed February 27, 2008.</ref>
Forsse died from congestive heart failure on March 19, 2014, aged 77.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/business/consumer/teddy-ruxpins-creator-ken-forsse-passes-away-n62996|title=Teddy Ruxpin's Creator, Ken Forsse, Passes Away|work=NBC News|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/ken-forsse-inventor-of-teddy-ruxpin-talking-toy-bear-dies-at-77/2014/04/03/176b83a4-bb28-11e3-9c3c-311301e2167d_story.html|title=Ken Forsse, inventor of Teddy Ruxpin talking toy bear, dies at 77|work=Washington Post|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref>
Forsse was not only one of the co-creators of Disney's Haunted Mansion attraction, but was also contracted by the Sid & Marty Krofft organization to design a haunted house attraction for their (short-lived) theme park in Atlanta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://plus.google.com/105281104953680569679/posts/1A5Y8CoGvmj|title=Last December 28th, 2013, my wife Zahava and I got the opportunity to visit…|publisher=Plus.google.com|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref>
== In other media == On February 19, 2018, independent filmmaker Billy Tooma announced that he was entering into development/pre-production on a feature-length documentary titled ''Ken Forsse: Come Dream with Me Tonight'', with a 2021 release date.<ref>{{Citation|last=Tooma|first=Billy|title=Ken Forsse: Come Dream with Me Tonight|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8031636/|others=Vincent Conroy, Jan Forsse, Josh Isaacson|accessdate=2018-02-20}}</ref>
