{{Infobox opera | name = Émilie | type = [[Monodrama]] | composer = [[Kaija Saariaho]] | image = | caption = | librettist = [[Amin Maalouf]] | language = French | based_on = life and writings of [[Émilie du Châtelet]] | premiere_date = {{Start date|2010|03|01|df=y}} | premiere_location = [[Opéra National de Lyon]] }} '''''Émilie''''' is an [[opera]] – specifically a 9-scene, 75-minute [[monodrama]] for [[soprano]] – by Finnish composer [[Kaija Saariaho]] (b. 1952)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://musicologynow.ams-net.org/2016/06/saariahos-lamour-de-loin-first-woman.html|title=Saariaho's L'amour de loin: First Woman Composer in a Century at the Metropolitan Opera|website=musicologynow.ams-net.org|access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref> to a [[libretto]] by [[Amin Maalouf]]. It was written in 2008.<ref>[http://www.sikorski.de/575/en/0/a/0/oper/1037688_emilie_oper.html ''Émilie''] at [[Hans Sikorski|Sikorski]]</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2010|title=NEWS SECTION|jstor=40794473|journal=Tempo|volume=64|issue=252|pages=115–117|doi=10.2307/40794473}}</ref> Based on the life and writings of Marquise [[Émilie du Châtelet]] (1706-1749),<ref>[http://www.chesternovello.com/Default.aspx?TabId=2434&State_2912=2&newsId_2912=1907 ''Émilie''] at [[Music Sales Group|Chester & Novello]]: synopsis, premiere information</ref> the work premiered at the [[Opéra National de Lyon|Opéra de Lyon]], France, on 1 March 2010, with Finnish soprano [[Karita Mattila]], its dedicatee. It recounts the achievements of the [[mathematician]], physicist, and [[Mistress (lover)|mistress]] of [[Voltaire]]: the first woman to establish an international scientific reputation, with pioneering work in the study of [[fire]].
The opera ''Émilíe'' is based on the actual biography of [[Émilie du Châtelet]], who was a contemporary intellectual to, as well as the [[Mistress (lover)|mistress]] of, [[Voltaire]]. She also took another lover later who fathered her child. The [[childbirth]] led to her death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womeninscience.history.msu.edu/Biography/C-4A-0/marquise-du-chtelet/|title=Women in Science {{!}} Biographies {{!}} Marquise Du Châtelet|website=womeninscience.history.msu.edu|access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref> In the plot of the opera, her character's arias are linked to the birth of the child and of her significant scholarship. The [[soprano]] soloist is seen in character pregnant and penning new ideas as the opera begins. The subject of the work depicted in the opera was an actual French translation of technical writing in ''[[Elements of the Philosophy of Newton|Eléments de la philosophie de Newton]]'' (1738). Though her French translation of what is also known simply as ''[[Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica|Principia]] by'' [[Isaac Newton]] was published posthumously in 1759, it remains a definitive text.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2016/entries/emilie-du-chatelet/|title=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|last=Detlefsen|first=Karen|date=2016|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|editor-last=Zalta|editor-first=Edward N.|edition=Winter 2016}}</ref> [[Émilie du Châtelet|Châtelet]] died 10 years prior to its publication. Composer Saariaho uses creative license to dramatically and sonically set the two births for solo soprano in a historical [[monodrama]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://saariaho.org/works/emilie/|title=Emilie « Kaija Saariaho|website=saariaho.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-17}}</ref>
The context of women characters and roles in [[opera]]s from the 17th century to the present rarely address their role as scientists or scholars, not to mention [[childbirth]], making this composition and performance an intervention that expands the genre as studied in new or [[feminist musicology]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Opera_Or_The_Undoing_of_Women.html?id=dc4HeHS3ulMC|title=Opera, Or, The Undoing of Women|last=Clement|first=Catherine|date=1999|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|isbn=9780816635269|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7waGip0qN6sC&lpg=PP1&dq=susan%20mclary&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=susan%20mclary&f=false|title=Feminine Endings: Music, Gender, and Sexuality|last=McClary|first=Susan|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|isbn=9781452906362|language=en}}</ref> [[Émilie du Châtelet|Émilie]] is one of three "female-centered operas" by Saariaho exhibiting a sonic world that feminist musicologist [[Susan McClary]] opines as "a 'sensual version of [[modernism]],' one in which 'smoldering intensities' of desire find [[Human voice|voice]]."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2013/04/29/even-the-score|title=Even the Score|last=Ross|first=Alex|date=2013-04-22|work=The New Yorker|access-date=2017-11-17|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>
Since [[Émilie du Châtelet|Châtelet]] was actually tutored in mathematics by leading European scholars and her exceptional skills were thought to influence Voltaire's work,<ref name=":0" /> the scenery in the 2008 [[Opéra National de Lyon|Opera de Lyon]] production of the opera featured images of mathematical [[equation]]s as significant aspects of the set and scenery for the monodrama.
Reviews dubbed it a "[[Bluestocking|blue-stocking]] monodrama about the tension between intellect and nature." Billed as the third opera by [[Kaija Saariaho|Saariaho]], Emilie is more accurately a sister-piece to the [[oratorio]] [[La Passion de Simone]] (2006).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/classical/reviews/emilie-op-ra-national-de-lyon-lyon-france-1917293.html|title=Emilie, Opéra National de Lyon, Lyon, France|date=2010-03-07|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-11-05|language=en-GB}}</ref> The actual score is accessible online.<ref name=":1" />
